<div id="title-3341" class="section section-text-over-media section-title section-title-3341" data-viewport-height>
  <div class="text title-inner right bottom">
      <h1 class="story-title text-inner normal">Blanco River runs roughshod</h1>
      <h2 class="story-heading text-inner normal"><strong>After a foot of rain falls upstream, a wall of water rushes down the Blanco River into Wimberley, San Marcos and beyond.</strong></h2>
  </div>

  <div class="story-metadata right text">BY BEN WEAR / AMERICAN-STATESMAN<br />May 24, 2015</div>

  <div class="background-overlay">
    
  </div>
</div>

<script>
  //IE9 fix to stop audio playing
  var video = document.getElementById('video-title-3341')
    if (video){
      video.muted = true;
    }
  ViewportHeight.attachTo(document.getElementById('title-3341'));
  if ('performance' in window) {
    window.performance.mark('titleEnd');
  }
</script>
<div id="scrollmation-two-column-4000" class="section section-scrollmation scrollmation-two-column section-two-column-4000" data-possible-scrollmation data-scrollmation-container="#scrollmation-two-column-4000" data-viewport-height data-viewport-height-property="min-height">
  <div class="two-column-grid">
    <div class="column column-left main-column scrollmation-text">
      
        <div class="block text-block"><p>Central Texans have been watching and hoping for a “rain bomb” to thoroughly extinguish a years-long drought and replenish dangerously low reservoirs. A former governor even suggested that Texans pray for such relief.  </p><aside class="scrollmation-inline " data-copy-element data-media-ratio="1.4" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-scrollmation-slide>
<img alt="David Barry consoles his 5 year old daughter Marley while she tries to sleep in a flood evacuee room created at the San Marcos Activity Center. The Barry family was evacuated from their apartment at 4 a.m. Sunday morning and was waiting to hear if they could return.ERIKA RICH / FOR AMERICAN-STATESMAN" class="inline-image edit-image-button" data-min-width-1401="./media/err-san-marcos-flooding-mr_218exdb.jpg" src="./media/err-san-marcos-flooding-lr_hgobzfz.jpg">
<p class="caption">David Barry consoles his 5 year old daughter Marley while she tries to sleep in a flood evacuee room created at the San Marcos Activity Center. The Barry family was evacuated from their apartment at 4 a.m. Sunday morning and was waiting to hear if they could return.<br/><br/>ERIKA RICH / FOR AMERICAN-STATESMAN</p>
</img></aside>

<p>Overnight Saturday, that big rain came, dumping up to a foot of rain over a large expanse of the Hill County, Austin and points to the east. The rainfall sparked a rapid rise in storage lakes throughout the area, but the storm exacted a steep price.  </p>
<p>A Hays County man died and three people were reported missing in historic flooding along the Blanco River that inundated sections of Blanco, Wimberley, San Marcos, Martindale and Luling. A thousand or more people are left homeless.  </p>
<p>In Wimberley, the river at its height reached at least 41 feet deep — the water gauge washed out at that point, officials said — about 8 feet above its all-time high in 1929 and 28 feet above flood stage.  </p><aside class="scrollmation-inline " data-copy-element data-media-ratio="1.4" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-scrollmation-slide>
<img alt="From left, Mark Norris, walking in black T-shirt, Retha Norris, Ally Smith and Christina Norris are rescued by firefighters after they clung in a tree at their home on South Old Stagecoach Drive in Kyle.JAY JANNER / AMERICAN-STATESMAN" class="inline-image edit-image-button" data-min-width-1401="./media/jwj-stagecoach-01-mr_w6pnxo1.jpg" src="./media/jwj-stagecoach-01-lr_4ultmz5.jpg">
<p class="caption">From left, Mark Norris, walking in black T-shirt, Retha Norris, Ally Smith and Christina Norris are rescued by firefighters after they clung in a tree at their home on South Old Stagecoach Drive in Kyle.<br/><br/>JAY JANNER / AMERICAN-STATESMAN</p>
</img></aside>

<p>The man who died, whose name was not released, was discovered in San Marcos Sunday afternoon, said Ken Bell, San Marcos’ emergency management coordinator. Separately, Hays County officials were searching for three missing Wimberley residents.  </p>
<p>“We’re looking at over a thousand properties damaged,” Bell said. “We’re into the hundreds of just missing homes.”  </p></div>
      
    </div>

    <div class="column margin-left secondary-column position-static">
      <div class="scrollmation-slides" data-copy-elements=".section-two-column-4000 [data-copy-element]" data-scrollmation-slides>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div><style>
  
</style>

<div id="wimberley-1694" class="section section-media section-media-youtube section-media-1694" data-viewport-height  data-viewport-height-ignore-orientation="portrait">
  

  
    <iframe id="iframe-wimberley-1694" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/G6bSrSLSN8A?enablejsapi=1&rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen data-viewport-height></iframe>
    <script>
      ViewportHeight.attachTo(document.getElementById('iframe-wimberley-1694'));
    </script>
  


  
</div>

<script>
  ViewportHeight.attachTo(document.getElementById('wimberley-1694'));
</script><div id="scrollmation-two-column-4001" class="section section-scrollmation scrollmation-two-column section-two-column-4001" data-possible-scrollmation data-scrollmation-container="#scrollmation-two-column-4001" data-viewport-height data-viewport-height-property="min-height">
  <div class="two-column-grid">
    <div class="column column-left main-column scrollmation-text">
      
        <div class="block text-block"><p>Hays County, San Marcos and Wimberley officials ordered a 9 p.m. Sunday curfew for those two cities and nearby unincorporated areas south of FM 150 because of safety concerns over downed power lines and damaged roads.  </p><aside class="scrollmation-inline " data-copy-element data-media-ratio="1.4" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-scrollmation-slide>
<img alt="Blanco River floodwaters destroyed the Fischer Store Road bridge near Wimberley.JAY JANNER / AMERICAN-STATESMAN" class="inline-image edit-image-button" data-min-width-1401="./media/jwj-flood-fisher-bridge-mr_gt4rnzn.jpg" src="./media/jwj-flood-fisher-bridge-lr_zhjguog.jpg">
<p class="caption">Blanco River floodwaters destroyed the Fischer Store Road bridge near Wimberley.<br/><br/>JAY JANNER / AMERICAN-STATESMAN</p>
</img></aside>

<p>Bridges were washed out on Fischer Store Road west of Wimberley and FM 165 east of Blanco. Even Interstate 35 was closed for a couple of hours at dawn Sunday in San Marcos when the Blanco River overtopped the highway.  </p>
<p>The storm, which lasted from early Saturday evening until daybreak Sunday, caused lesser flooding on a number of other area creeks and rivers that in general caused less significant damage. It spawned a tornado in Dripping Springs that damaged a trailer park and what some people thought might have been tornadic winds — National Weather Service officials could not confirm this — that tore down trees and damaged property in Austin and some Williamson County suburbs.  </p></div><div class="block media-block media-block-youtube">
<div class="inline-media">
<div class="inline-youtube">
<iframe allowfullscreen frameborder="0" height="315" id="scrollmation-two-column-4001-block-2" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/Y4wMt1ikrRw?enablejsapi=1&amp;rel=0" width="560"></iframe>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="block text-block"><p>Those winds, and the fallen trees, knocked out power to 30,000 Austin Energy customers and about 6,000 Pedernales Electric Co-operative customers. All but about 2,800 Austin Energy customers had electricity again by mid-afternoon Sunday, Austin Energy spokesman Robert Cullick said. About 3,300 PEC customers were still without power early Sunday evening.  </p>
<p>Officials had to temporarily close more than 200 low-water crossings in the Austin area, and emergency workers had to rescue dozens of people from rushing waters.  </p><aside class="scrollmation-inline " data-copy-element data-media-ratio="1.4" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-scrollmation-slide>
<img alt="Several cabins along the Blanco in Wimberley near the RM 12 bridge were destroyed.JAY JANNER / AMERICAN-STATESMAN" class="inline-image edit-image-button" data-min-width-1401="./media/jwj-flood-cabin-mr_f81pco6.jpg" src="./media/jwj-flood-cabin-lr_vsrigy0.jpg">
<p class="caption">Several cabins along the Blanco in Wimberley near the RM 12 bridge were destroyed.<br/><br/>JAY JANNER / AMERICAN-STATESMAN</p>
</img></aside>

<p>But south of Austin, the damage was profound. And as the water moves southeast toward the Gulf of Mexico, Gonzales, Cuero and Victoria could be threatened, said Bill West, general manager of Guadalupe-Blanco River Authority.  </p>
<p>Rain is predicted for Central Texas again Monday.  </p>
<p>“We were going to retire here,” Wimberley resident Bob Harla said Sunday as clean-up workers pumped brown water out of the house he recently bought on the banks of the Blanco River. “I don’t know what we’re going to do now.”  </p></div>
      
    </div>

