<div id="scrollmation-two-column-4003" class="section section-scrollmation scrollmation-two-column section-two-column-4003" data-possible-scrollmation data-scrollmation-container="#scrollmation-two-column-4003" data-viewport-height data-viewport-height-property="min-height">
  <div class="two-column-grid">
    <div class="column column-left main-column scrollmation-text">
      
        <div class="block text-block"><p>The San Marcos River already was well out of its banks near Luling late Sunday and crested at 38 feet, officials said. Flood stage there is 21 feet.  </p><aside class="scrollmation-inline " data-copy-element data-media-ratio="1.4" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-scrollmation-slide>
<img alt="Lake Travis gained another six feet of water to reach 52 percent full by Sunday afternoon.RODOLFO GONZALEZ / AMERICAN-STATESMAN" class="inline-image edit-image-button" data-min-width-1401="./media/rgz-lake-travis-06-mr_cyxr2mo.jpg" src="./media/rgz-lake-travis-06-lr_5om5ysw.jpg">
<p class="caption">Lake Travis gained another six feet of water to reach 52 percent full by Sunday afternoon.<br/><br/>RODOLFO GONZALEZ / AMERICAN-STATESMAN</p>
</img></aside>

<p>“Given the fact that the water has just begun to recede, we haven’t begun a preliminary damage assessment,” said Martin Ritchey, Cameron County emergency management director. “But we know that homes will have been inundated, damaged, knocked down and destroyed from this event.”  </p></div><div class="block media-block media-block-youtube">
<div class="inline-media">
<div class="inline-youtube">
<iframe allowfullscreen frameborder="0" height="315" id="scrollmation-two-column-4003-block-2" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/xVdp2OfDGX4?enablejsapi=1&amp;rel=0" width="560"></iframe>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="block text-block"><p>In Austin, Barton Creek flooded and sent muddy water spewing over the dam at Barton Springs Pool, which will require considerable cleanup before reopening. Emergency officials at mid-afternoon had to rescue a person who had climbed a tree to escape the rising waters.  </p>
<p>However, the positive effect on Austin’s drinking supply — the waters impounded in lakes Travis and Buchanan — was significant and immediate.  </p>
<p>Lake Travis, which at the beginning of the year was at 33 percent of capacity and 58 feet below a level considered full, had gone up about 13 feet recently as the area saw three straight weeks of rain. Overnight, it jumped another 6 feet. By late Sunday afternoon, it stood at almost 647 feet — more than 52 percent full — and was still rising rapidly. Buchanan, which missed out on much of the heavier rain and is considerably larger, has gone up only about a foot in the past week.  </p>
<p>But the storm more than filled up Lake Georgetown to the north on the San Gabriel River and Canyon Lake on the Guadalupe River south of San Marcos.  </p>
<p>“If you look at the history books, the droughts we’ve had, that’s what breaks them: a rainy system that eventually produces a flood event,” said West, the Guadalupe-Blanco River Authority leader. “I think this will go down as the five-year drought of 2011 to 2015. And this is what ended it.”  </p></div>
      
    </div>

